Success criteria
The final engine succeeds when a dry-run can prove:


All source LBs matched or planned for creation
All source TGs matched/created
All listeners matched/created/updated
All listener rules discovered
All listener rule priorities compared
All listener rule conditions compared
All listener actions remapped to DR TG ARNs
All HTTPS/TLS certificates mapped to DR ACM certs
No ambiguous subnet mappings
No unmatched routing dependencies


The report must distinguish:

LB object parity
Listener parity
Rule parity
Certificate parity
TG parity


Do not report “Load Balancer in sync” as full routing parity unless its listeners and rules are also in sync.


This is enough for someone to understand the project, but not enough for someone to finish it to the standard you’re aiming for.
After working with you on this project from the beginning, there are many things that are not obvious from the code alone. These are architectural decisions we’ve made together over months of iteration. If I were handing this to another senior engineer, I’d include those as “design principles.”
Here are the most important ones.

1. The philosophy of the project
This is not a migration tool.
It is not a cloning tool.
It is an enterprise reconciliation engine.

that means: 
Production

↓

Discover

↓

Compare

↓

Detect drift

↓

Safely converge DR toward Production


The goal is idempotent convergence, not recreation.

2. Safety is more important than automation
One principle we’ve followed throughout:
Never guess.
For example:
If subnet mapping is ambiguous
↓
Do not create the LB.
If certificate mapping is ambiguous
↓
Do not update the listener.
If TG mapping is ambiguous
↓
Do not modify the listener.
The engine should always prefer:

Manual Review over possibly incorrect automation  


3. Treat AWS as the source of truth
The engine should not require:
	• spreadsheets
	• subnet maps
	• JSON lookup files
	• manually maintained subnet IDs
instead:

DescribeSubnets

DescribeRouteTables

DescribeListeners

DescribeRules

DescribeTargetGroups


should provide everything needed.
The config should contain only:

Environment

Policy

Optional overrides

nothing else.


4. Every comparison should be deterministic
For example:
Instead of:
Looks similar,
 every comparison should explain:
Matched because

Name

↓

Normalized

↓

Role

↓

AZ

↓

CIDR

↓

Validated

That makes reports explainable.


